## Full-Body Character Replacement Pipeline

## Prompt

```text
Analyze both input images carefully before generating the result.

imagem_0 = ORIGINAL (scene structure and pose base)

imagem_1 = MODELO (complete character source)

TASK

Perform a complete full-body character replacement.

The goal is to replace the entire person in imagem_0 with the person from imagem_1, transferring all visual characteristics of the character from imagem_1 while preserving the scene structure from imagem_0.

The final result must show the person from imagem_1 naturally occupying the same pose, position and camera perspective originally present in imagem_0.

STEP 1 — IMAGE ANALYSIS

First analyze imagem_1 (MODELO) and extract all character-defining attributes including:

- full facial identity and biometrics
- face shape and bone structure
- eyes, eyebrows, nose, lips and facial proportions
- skin tone, skin texture and skin marks
- hair color, hairstyle, density and texture
- clothing design, garments and textile appearance
- accessories such as jewelry, earrings, necklaces, watches or rings
- tattoos, piercings, scars or other defining body markers
- visible makeup and stylistic features
- exposed body characteristics and proportions

Then analyze imagem_0 (ORIGINAL) and identify the scene structure that must be preserved:

- body pose and orientation
- camera perspective and angle
- framing and focal length
- subject position in the scene
- background and environment
- lighting direction and shadow behavior
- color temperature and ambient light
- depth of field and focus characteristics
- overall scene composition

STEP 2 — ATTRIBUTE TRANSFER

Transfer from imagem_1 (MODELO):

- complete facial identity
- hairstyle and hair appearance
- skin characteristics and tone
- full clothing and garments
- all accessories and ornaments
- tattoos, piercings and body marks
- stylistic elements such as makeup or fashion details
- the complete visual appearance of the character

Preserve from imagem_0 (ORIGINAL):

- pose and body orientation
- camera perspective and framing
- spatial placement of the subject
- lighting conditions and shadows
- environmental interaction
- background and scene composition

STEP 3 — REPLACEMENT RULES

Replace the entire person present in imagem_0 with the character from imagem_1.

The generated subject must reproduce the appearance of imagem_1 including:

- face
- hair
- clothing
- accessories
- tattoos and piercings
- stylistic and visual traits

The subject must appear naturally integrated into the pose and scene originally present in imagem_0.

Do not modify the environment or background.

STEP 4 — INTEGRATION REQUIREMENTS

Ensure:

- correct adaptation of the character from imagem_1 into the pose of imagem_0
- anatomically correct body placement
- natural alignment of head, neck and shoulders
- realistic clothing behavior following the pose
- consistent interaction between clothing and body posture
- seamless integration between the subject and the environment
- proper scaling between subject and scene

STEP 5 — LIGHTING AND REALISM

Adapt the transferred character to the lighting conditions of imagem_0:

- same light direction
- same shadow behavior
- same color temperature
- coherent exposure and contrast
- realistic highlights on skin, hair and clothing

Maintain photorealistic detail including:

- natural skin texture and pores
- realistic hair strands
- textile microtexture in clothing
- authentic accessory materials

STEP 6 — ERROR PREVENTION

Avoid:

- facial distortion
- pose alteration
- warped anatomy
- accessory disappearance
- clothing deformation
- lighting inconsistency
- identity blending between subjects
- background modification

FINAL GOAL

Generate a photorealistic full-body character replacement where the person from imagem_1 appears naturally in the pose, perspective and environment originally present in imagem_0, carrying all visual characterist.
```
